column1: How many of the BRIC countries will report positive annualised growth for the quarter ending in December 2015?
column6: ['Economic Indicators']
column11: Brazil, Russia, India and China make up the BRIC countries; all four have been experiencing slowdowns in growth and enter 2016 facing distinct economic challenges (The World in 2016). Annualised quarterly growth rates measure the change in real GDP compared to the same quarter of the previous year. The question will be suspended on 31 December 2015 and will close once the BRIC governments release annualized growth for the quarter ending in December of 2015. Media coverage of the growth rates for the quarter ending September of 2015 can be seen here: Brazil , Russia, India, China.

Based upon the wording of the headline question, it seems to refer to a positive growth for the 4th quarter alone. Note that quarterly GDP is always based on the change in GDP from the prior quarter (i.e. Q3). "Annualized" means you take a quarterly figure and annualize it (1+ r/100)^4. However, reading the question description, it seems to refer to annual (not annualized) growth (i.e. ending GDPQ4'15/ending GDPQ4'14 - 1) or year over year growth. If that is what is desired, a much clearer way to phrase the question would be how many of the countries would show positive YoY real GDP growth at the end of Q4 2015 or even more simply, show positive GDP growth for the full year 2015. There is almost no way for either Brazil or Russia to have positive GDP growth for the full year 2015.

Brazil and Russia continue to suffer from low commodity prices and political actors who either cannot or will not make the structural and political changes necessary to improve growth. But it is possible Russia posts modestly positive growth in Q4, but unlikely. It's more likely they surprise to the upside in 2016 if at all.

Growth in China has slowed down and Modi's policies will take time to accelerate growth in India. Solow growth model suggests that they will keep growing albeit with erratically, until they are at par with the developed economies. Same logic applies to Brazil and Russia but they face dire short-term risks. Brazil's commodity exports have collapsed and her finances with it. Russia's oil and gas revenues have collapsed, military expenditures have gone up. Current account and fiscal balances adjust slowly. Besides, they face corruption scandals and sanctions as the cherry on top. However, there is some chance that one of them (probably Russia) posts mildly positive growth. First, reporting is a bit muddy; they can report positive as an national accounting wonder. Second, military expenditures have stimulus effect, possibly large in Russia's case where the economy is tethering. Finally, oil and gas prices have declined but we don't know much about the volume of contracts state-owned oil and gas companies signed.
